What's Holding Back the Accuracy
RQ1 — Classification (The model is okay, but could be better)
Current problems:

20 epochs and one hidden layer of 64 neurons is relatively small for a dataset of 250,000 rows
The threshold of 0.0 is fixed — it's not tuned to find the optimal precision/recall balance
No learning rate scheduling — the learning rate stays flat the entire training which means the model stops improving efficiently in later epochs
Dropout of 0.3 might be too aggressive, killing useful neurons during training

What I'd try:

Increase epochs to 50–100 with early stopping so it stops automatically when it stops improving
Add a learning rate scheduler that reduces the rate as training progresses
Try different classification thresholds (0.3, 0.4) instead of fixed 0.0 to find the sweet spot between precision and recall
Experiment with wider layers — 256 → 128 → 64 instead of 128 → 64 → 32


RQ2 — Regression (This is a deeper problem)
Current problems:

R² of 0.16 is not primarily a modeling problem — it's a data problem
The features in this dataset are survey-based lifestyle indicators, not direct physiological measurements
BMI is heavily influenced by genetics, metabolism, and detailed diet — none of which exist in this dataset
The model is compressing predictions toward the mean because extreme BMI cases are underrepresented in training

What I'd try:

Feature engineering — create interaction terms like Age × PhysActivity or combine related features before feeding them in
Target transformation — apply log transformation to BMI before training to compress the extreme values and help the model handle outliers better
Oversampling extreme BMI cases — similar to class weighting in RQ1, give the model more exposure to high and low BMI examples
Increase epochs significantly — the loss curves showed both models nearly plateaued, meaning more training time could still help


The Honest Answer
For RQ1 the fixes above would genuinely push performance higher. For RQ2 no amount of architecture tuning will dramatically change the R² because the ceiling is set by the data itself, not the model. To meaningfully improve BMI prediction you'd need richer features — actual dietary data, physical measurements, or metabolic indicators — that this survey dataset simply doesn't contain.